reporter_caption.center: COLONIAL PONTIAC v. GEN. MOTORS CORP, 614 So.2d 1204 (Fla.App. 1 Dist. 1993)

caption.center: COLONIAL PONTIAC, INC., APPELLANT, v. GENERAL MOTORS CORPORATION/PONTIAC

court.center: District Court of Appeal of Florida, First District.

opinion.posture: An appeal from an order of the Department of Highway Safety Motor Vehicles.
opinion.attorneys:
James D. Adams, of Adams Quinton, P.A., Boca Raton, for appellant.
James J. Williams, Office of General Counsel, General Motors Corp., Detroit, and Vasilis C. Katsafanas, of Cabaniss, Burke Wagner, Orlando, for appellee.
opinion.opinion_text:
We affirm the final order of the Department of Highway Safety and Motor Vehicles to the extent it adopts the findings of fact and conclusions of law in the hearing officer's recommended order approving appellees' application to establish a new Pontiac dealership in Dade County. However, because it was not relevant to the proceedings below, conducted pursuant to section 320.642, Florida Statutes, we are not concernedPage 1205 with the remaining language in the final order holding that the proposed dealer be granted a franchise license upon compliance with all applicable requirements of section 320.27, and all applicable department rules. Such language is clearly gratuitous and cannot be read as granting an entitlement to a license absent further action on the department's part pursuant to section320.27.
AFFIRMED.
MINER and WOLF, JJ., concur.
